%N A396116 Consider the square spiral with its cells numbered starting at 0. Four players take turns and place knights at the smallest unoccupied cell not attacked by an existing knight of a different player. Sequence lists squares occupied by the first player.
%C A396116 A variant of A392177 with four players.
%H A396116 Rémy Sigrist, <a href="/A396116/b396116.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A396116 Brady Haran, Jonas Karlsson, and N. J. A. Sloane, <a href="https://youtu.be/UiX4CFIiegM">Red & Black Knights (extraordinary result)</a>; <a href="https://youtu.be/VgmDuBCayPw">Amazing Chessboard Patterns (extra)</a>, YouTube Numberphile videos, May 2026
%H A396116 Jonas Karlsson, <a href="/A396116/a396116.png">Four knights with colors black, red, cyan, purple. Close-up, 200 of each color.</a>
%H A396116 Jonas Karlsson, <a href="/A396116/a396116_1.png">Four knights with colors black, red, cyan, purple. Zoom-out, 60K of each color.</a>
%H A396116 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A396116/a396116_2.png">Four knights with colors Red, Green, Blue, Yellow, after ten million knights have been placed.</a>
%H A396116 Rémy Sigrist, <a href="/A396116/a396116.gp.txt">PARI program</a>
